this man is decomposing in front of our eyes. he speaks so slowly and is so unorganized with his thought process. he keeps couching into the mic and straight uo took a swig of cough syrup right from the bottle. only reason I gave him a 2 is because he pours his water into a glass and is the most adorable old man.

hes such a slow speaker and says uh so often it's so hard to pay attention. also spent a whole class coughing and blowing his nose into the mic without even apologizing once. his slides are messy and not easy to follow him in lecture so makes everything worse. haven't had the exam yet, but im scared bc I can't listen to him at all

I had Dr. Staines for an online course - I believe this was the beginning of the end. He was not very tech savvy and his lectures were quite boring. However, his examinations were fair - they expected knowledge of the content, typically not an enriched understanding. I would not take him again.

He did asynchronous videos but I had to watch them at 2x speed for them to be bearable. I'm not sure if he has a stutter but he talks extremely slow and with a lot of "uh"s. I'm pretty sure if I had him in-person I would've fallen asleep 2 minutes into the lecture. He's a nice guy and all but just take someone else it's not worth it.
Lectures were very boring and unorganized. However, the exam was of normal difficulty. I wouldn't recommend him if you actually wanted to learn.

Definitely try and avoid...his lectures are nearly unwatchable as he mumbles over every word and breathes heavy into the mic. Also just uses voiceovers so it's hard to see what he's referring to on diagrams. Exams were average difficulty and teaching yourself with the textbook is probably the way to go.

Dr. Staines is not an overly engaging lecturer nor an organized professor. While he does occasionally include useful information that is not on his slides, he does not seem super passionate about what he teaches. He did not organize the course Brightspace very well, so students sort of had to figure out what was going on themselves.

He is genuinely a really sweet man, and he really wants his students to succeed. I do not want to comment any hate on this man, however, his lectures are not very enjoyable. He only provides audio recordings over his slides, with no pointer, making it very difficult to follow only. Especially for neurophysiology. Very warm-hearted though.

He knows his subject... just really struggles to teach it (especially in online format). He can't work his audio on his slides and his narration style makes it very difficult to ever stay engaged. I recommend avoiding him so that you have the chance to enjoy how fascinating anatomy can actually be.

Cannot stand this professor. I really try to enjoy his lectures and pay attention in them. But he is awful! His powerpoints are disorganized and messy, he clears his throat after every sentence, stumbles over his words, mumbles to himself and says "uh", and overall does not know how to teach. I am sure he is a nice guy but AVOID HIM AT ALL COSTS.

His lecturing style was very inconvenient. He just had recordings of his voice on a slideshow. You couldn't see him gesturing at anything, and it was overall difficult to follow along with. Might have just been easier to read the textbook and teach it to myself.

While I am not a fan of using power point voice overs as lectures, Prof. Staines taught the material very well. For his class I found the best way to study was to use his lecture slides and take notes. On the first page of each lecture he lists the important topics - some you will need the textbook for to get more detail.

If this man were a spice, he would be flour. He is so bland, I don't know how anyone manages to stay awake during his lectures. "Lecture" is a term used very loosely here. They consist of narrated PowerPoints (long audioclips of the prof mumbling and forgetting what to say) filled with confusing, disorganized slides. Avoid if you value your sanity.

I got 100% on both midterms with Carnegie and now Im struggling to get through this last neurophys section with Staines. The individual audio clips on each slide makes the lectures so long and hard to not lose focus. I wish he had made lecture videos. Hes a good teacher but I personally feel is less organized with the transition to online school.
His lectures are so boring and very repetitive. It is very hard to go from professor Carnegie to him

He was a really sweet prof that I think just struggled a little with online school. He did have office hours weekly that I found very helpful and stayed past class time to ensure everyones answers were answered properly and were understood. I enjoyed his style of teaching and him as an individual!
Horrible presenter with monotone voice and no actual useful additional information. Simply reads words off a powerpoint at a slow pace

He really could've done better & I hope he does in the future. I cannot stress how much crash course & the textbook saved my grade (although respiratory system with him was a little more manageable). He is a very confused man. His slides are awful and so unorganized. He seems very sweet and knowledgeable about the anatomy we were learning but he is terrible at delivering information in a way for students to understand. His exams werent too hard. Very confusing class. Do not recommend.

rComments: He trails off and is hard to follow. I fell asleep in every one of his classes and left partway through other classes. Ask him specific questions in class and he will he will help you! Dr Staines is very hard to understand. His explanations are unclear so the textbook is a lifesaver. Avoid him if you can.

Dr. Staines has a very monotone voice although he can be engaging. His multiple choice questions are by far the most complicated and unfair! Dr. Staines comes off as a very nice guy. He tries to explain concepts by acting out examples (ex. walking quickly, grabbing something). His slides are terrible and very non specific. He misses a large amount of the txt book content in his slide shows. His voice is very monotone and you fall asleep during 90% of his lectures.

Monotone, mumbles, & slides are incredibly useless. AVOID

He means well and you can tell he knows the material, he just has a tough time teaching it. I would definitely recommend using the textbook to fill in any gaps from the slides. His tests aren't the most clear but they aren't the worst either.

rComments: Dr Staines is probably the worst prof I've had at uOttawa. His lectures are boring and he struggles at formulating sentences, so his lectures end up being more confusing than they should be. He often goes off on tangents about non-relevant subjects. Stay home and read the textbook.

Some people say he has a monotonous voice, and that he's boring.  Sure anatomy isn't always the most interesting class, but he really makes the effort to put some humour and movement into his classes, which keeps them interesting. As a more visual, kinesthetic learner, I appreciated his enthusiasm and movements/actions to get across concepts.

He has a very monotonous voice but he tries to keep the class interested by simplifying his explanations and making a few jokes or funny movements. I had a hard time listening to him talk because he has one of those voices that easily make you sleep. The few times I was awake were really interesting though and made reading the textbook easier.

Yes he's a good guy, but here's the thing: we're NOT rating his personality, we're critiquing his teaching skills. I hate to sound rude but I did not understand a single thing from his lectures, if it wasn't for the book then I would've failed. His lectures are very monotonous and dull, which makes it REALLY hard to concentrate.

Not always clear in his lecturesinstructions, but Staines is very smart, and very sweet! His final is not difficult if you study and know your stuff. Study his slides, not the textbook! Easy A+ if you review regularly.

Not as bad as I expected.  His slides are incomprehensible and completely disorganized, so you have to read the textbook to understand. Upside: very punctual and clear when answering questions via email Downside: monotone voice hard puts class to sleep
Neuro is usually boring, so he tries his best to be funny and make it exciting but it doesn't work. Leaned most of the stuff form the book

Professor Staines knows his stuff, but he has a very monotonous voice, so your attention may wander a bit. In his defence, he does try his best to make the lecture interesting, and he means well.  I found his midterm and exam questions fairly easy; just read the slides in class and know them well, no textbook reading necessary.

Decent prof overall but I agree it's difficult sitting through his lectures without feeling your eyes start to droop... He is funny though, made me laugh at least once every lecture so I'll give him that! Komorowski or Savory were my top 2... I recommend them if you have the chance.

let me preface this by saying I have an 88 in this course, and did well on Staines' part of the exam. he is a horrendous communicator. his slides are cryptic and borderline incoherent forcing you to take detailed notes during class. he is obsessed with anatomy rather than concepts. makes the material unnecessary inaccessible at first glance.

Good prof, very interesting in class (funny and entertaining). Goes through material fairly quickly so you need to do readings in the textbook to understand everything. Midterms are a bit tough but theyre MC so it's not too bad! Overall he was a pretty good prof and made class interesting.

very hard final exam with very specific details. confusing and unclear. in my opinion it was very difficult switching profs before the final because it's hard to know another prof's testing style for something worth so much of your mark! had a 90% going in to the final and his final ruined my grade :(
He mumbles a LOT and it's very frustrating. His strange sound effects were not useful. He is not concise with his explanations and tends to ramble. One of the worst professors for this course.

I have had this prof the neurology portions of PHS3240 and ANP1107. I found in the ANP class his exam was considerably more difficult than in the PHS class.  He is a great professor and really tries to get the content across to all students. He is really knowledgeable and approachable.

He is entertaining and "cool" but consequently makes himself appear less intelligent than I presume he is. He will pull some questions out of no where and will expect you to know the material from A-Z.

He's cool I like him. Some pple find him boring but I guess it depends on your level of interest in the material. Not a great prof when compared to the other profs teaching anatomy. He tries to make lectures interesting with sound effects, but its a fail...Just read the textbook on your own and you can get a good grade.
